               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t16881205-12-off52-c47" targOrder="Y" targets="t16881205-12-defend63 t16881205-12-off52 t16881205-12-verdict53"></join>
         
               <p>
            
               
                  <persName id="t16881205-12-defend63" type="defendantName">
                     Thomas 
                     Sherwood
                  <interp inst="t16881205-12-defend63" type="surname" value="Sherwood"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16881205-12-defend63" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16881205-12-defend63" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
            , was Tryed for <rs id="t16881205-12-off52" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t16881205-12-off52" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16881205-12-off52" type="offenceSubcategory" value="animalTheft"></interp>
               stealing a Gelding, value 8 l.
            </rs> out of the Grounds of one 
               
                  <persName id="t16881205-12-victim65" type="victimName">
                     Thomas 
                     Rogers
                  <interp inst="t16881205-12-victim65" type="surname" value="Rogers"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16881205-12-victim65" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16881205-12-victim65" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t16881205-12-off52 t16881205-12-victim65"></join>
                  </persName>
               
             in July last. The Proof against him was, That upon missing the Gelding, and inquiry made after him, the Prisoner was taken upon his back at a place called Southern, in the County of Middlesex, where they were seized together. To this he pleaded Justification, insisting, That he bought that Horse in Smithfield, though without Tolling; saying, He had lived a considerable Time with a person in Southwark who keeps Livery Stables: And so far insinnated into the good Opinion of the Jury, though no Evidence appeared on his behalf; That it created in them so great a belief of his Innocence as to <rs id="t16881205-12-verdict53" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t16881205-12-verdict53" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               Acquit
            </rs> him.</p>
